Three standalone CLI binaries for the `steno` crate, each a thin driver over the lib's pipeline (`parse_source` → `expand_dict` → build/serialize) that reads the same `dict.steno` source and writes or reports on derived artifacts. None contains real dictionary logic — all of that lives upstream in the `steno` lib crate, and a signature change there (`Entry`, `BuildResult`, `parse_source`, `expand_dict`, `build_plain_dict`/`build_smart_dict`/`build_snippets`, `to_json`) breaks all three simultaneously.

All three independently reimplement the same `root()` helper resolving the workspace root as `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`, hardcoding that each binary lives two directories below the workspace root containing `dict.steno` and `out/` — moving the `steno` crate or these binaries breaks all three the same way, and any fix must be applied in three places. All three also call `expand_dict(&entries, None)` (no scoping/profile filter at expansion time) and dedupe collision reports through a `BTreeSet` before printing/counting, so repeated collisions on the same stroke/key never get double-reported across any of the binaries. All three use stringly-typed errors (`Result<_, String>`) funneled to a `fail()`-style handler that prints to stderr and returns `ExitCode::FAILURE`, never panicking on expected failure paths.

`build_dict.rs` produces the two Plover-facing JSON dictionaries (plain/smart) actually shipped to the device, guarding both against collisions *before* either file is written so a bad build never leaves a stale-plus-fresh mismatched pair. `build_nvim.rs` produces the companion Neovim-plugin artifacts (stroke→token lookup and token→snippet expansion), also refusing to touch `out/` at all if collisions are found. `measure.rs` is the odd one out: it writes nothing, instead building six variant configurations of the same dictionary (3 stroke pools × param/no-param shapes) purely to print a comparative size matrix; its no-param path relies on a hand-maintained `NOPARAM` stroke table that silently falls out of sync if `dict.steno`'s function-shape strokes change, with no error raised.